04899nam a22007575i 9780812293531DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20162017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979968364  a97808122935317 a10.9783/97808122935312doi  a(DE-B1597)480401  a(OCoLC)965773111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR851b.T47 2017eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a809/.93356223  aHK 13012rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50142:1 aThompson, Helen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFictional Matter :bEmpiricism, Corpuscles, and the Novel /cHelen Thompson. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b12 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Boyle’s Doctrine of Qualities -- tChapter 2. John Locke and Matter’s Power -- tChapter 3. Morbific Matter and Character’s Form -- tChapter 4. Race and the Corpuscle -- tChapter 5. Quality’s Qualities: Fielding’s Alchemical Imaginary -- tChapter 6. Fixing Sex: Richardson’s Clarissa -- tEpilogue. Denominating Oxygen -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a groundbreaking study of the relationship between chemistry and literary history, Helen Thompson explores the ways in which chemical conceptions of matter shaped eighteenth-century British culture. Although the scientific revolution championed experimental, sense-based knowledge, chemists claimed that perceptible bodies were made of invisible particles or "corpuscles." Neither modern elements nor classical atoms, corpuscles were reactive, divisible units of matter. Imperceptible but real, the corpuscle transformed empirical knowledge in early modern science and the novel.Thompson offers new analyses of the chemistry, alchemy, color theory, physiology, environmental science, and medicine pioneered by Robert Boyle, Isaac Newton, Stephen Hales, John Mitchell, John Arbuthnot, and Thomas Sydenham to argue that they shaped cultural conceptions of racial, class, sex, and species identity. Juxtaposing science with readings of novels by Daniel Defoe, Eliza Haywood, Jonathan Swift, Samuel Richardson, Henry Fielding, William Rufus Chetwood, and Penelope Aubin, she shows how, at the level of form as well as character, novels represent perceptual knowledge that refers not to innate essence but to dynamic and unstable relations.The realist narrative mode that experimental science bequeaths to literary history, Fictional Matter argues, does not transparently mirror perceptible objects. Instead, novels represent the forms and relations through which imperceptible particles stimulate sensory experience. In this lucid, revisionary analysis of corpuscular chemistry, Thompson advances a new account of the influence of experimental science and empirical knowledge on the emergent realist novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aChemistry in literature. 0aChemistryzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aEmpiricism in literature. 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and sciencezEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229353140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293531.jpg  a978-3-11-055030-6  Penn Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEB